text:
this was a gift i received in 2013 because i worked for tip-off anonymous, they thought i should write stories about criminals or a book, but i haven't solved any mystery yet.  i can maybe solve someone else's mystery, but not my own.  i remain an unsolved mystery because no investigator or criminal profiler can figure out why i always get harassed and stalked by psychos and dangerous men.  i don't have the looks or dress in a feminine way to get stalked.  some people told me it's because i have a doppelgänger or look-a-like from uitenhage and they are actually following her.  i never go to that town so i wouldn't know because someone once asked me if i live there.  another incident was when i was in woolworths some stranger asked me do i remember him from the keg and swan in humewood and i've never in my life been there neither have i seen him before.  i thought he must be on drugs because i don't know him and not interested in knowing him because he looked weird.  most people also think i'm from overseas that's why international people hack me from these russian countries.  i'm actually not sure if someone is impersonating me or looks like me, initially i thought someone is trying to look or dress like me.  men are not actually attracted to me once they get to know me and most men are not interested in me.  maybe it's because i am the only one who can figure people out, they don't want me to expose them.  especially in the workplace i always get harassed because men are afraid of me taking their job.  they don't want me to become a manager or have some position of authority because i will be very strict.  men don't want to work with someone like me.  there's something about me men don't like, not because they like me, they actually can't stand me.  i think it's because i'm too perfect i was supposed to be a nun or some religious character because i'm always celibate nobody can compete with me.  i can do more jobs than the average human and be good at anything i try to do even if i don't like it that's why men are jealous of me; i can do both feminine & masculine jobs. 
#gift #harassment #criminals #crime #mystery #portelizabeth #southafrica #metoo #writer

text:
😞he didn’t know he was actually being groomed, then sexually abused until he was actually abused.
.
🤫grooming allows sexual abuse offenders to have access to children, develop a 🤫secret and intimate relationship, then weeks, or either months later the relationship with them becomes sexual by touching, or non touching but still abusive.
.
😞many times children victims may not realize they have been abused because their body may have responded positively to the touch (most cases aren’t forced), or they weren’t actually touched but still abused.
.
📝preventative education will help empower your children to know when to tell, not to keep secrets, understand grooming, and stop the abuse before it begins.
.
#trauma #awareness #abuse #boys #metoo #sexualabuse #childhood #educateyourself #parenting

text: si hace poco la imagen de ‘beso en times square’ volvía a ser noticia por la reciente muerte del marinero que la protagoniza, george mendonsa, esta vez lo vuelve a ser, pero no la imagen, sino una estátua que la representa en el estado norteamericano de florida. desde el martes por la mañana la policía local está intentando localizar al autor o autora de un vandalismo que se ha producido en una estátua que recrea la escena de la fotografía a su imagen y semejanza, en la que han pintado un enorme #metoo (yo también) con grafiti rojo sobre la pierna de la joven que está siendo besada. por ahora la policía aún no ha dado con la identidad de l@s responsables, y calculan que los costes de limpieza del grafiti ascienden a mil dólares.

gop is dead. gop remains dead. and we have killed him. how shall we comfort ourselves, the murderers of all murderers? what was holiest and mightiest of all that the world has yet owned has bled to death under our knives: who will wipe this blood off us? what water is there for us to clean ourselves? what festivals of atonement, what sacred games shall we have to invent? is not the greatness of this deed too great for us? must we ourselves not become gods simply to appear worthy of it?

howlindsey doody

my brother is almost 10 years elder to me. i think i was 13 when this happened. i've always been a stubborn kid, always getting my way when i know i'm right. i don't remember what exactly was it but i was pissed at something, and it's a habit since a young age that i don't make a fuss. i just seethe in a corner and remain silent and look murderous. so my brother complained about it to our mom about it, and i'll never forget the words she said, never. it stinged back then and still does though it's almost a decade. she said to my brother," its okay beta, let it go. she'll grow in a few years and get married so you/we dont have to deal with her then. she'll be gone soon, don't worry." i happened to over hear it. i don't know if she was joking,but it really hurt. i mean i was only 13, was i such a burden and still am that you want to get rid of me?

text:
randy moss 
there is a distinction between "greatest" and "best". for example, jerry rice is the "greatest" wide receiver in nfl history. he has the records and the rings to back that up. but, if you're asking about the "best"? that's randy moss! in terms of playmaking ability that can change the game, moss can't be topped. he himself holds records and played in a couple of super bowls. but, that's not why randy is on here. yes, he's a mercurial talent. however, it's the drive and determination that got him to the league and what he's done afterward that impresses me. moss grew up in rand, west virginia, with a population of about 1,600. to say he was facing an uphill battle from the start would be an understatement. randy's college career began in fits and starts. he was going to play for notre dame, but after his involvement in a fight involving race (in west virginia?! shocked!) the fighting irish denied his enrollment. florida state was going to give him a chance, but he tested positive for marijuana after smoking a joint. yes, you read that right...one joint. so, they dismissed him. and just like that, the once promising career of randy moss was in jeopardy of never happening, having been shuttered before ever getting off the ground. that has happened to countless young black men. again...a joint! moss eventually ended up at marshall, a small school in a lesser division, but was still able to make it to the league. after his playing days were over, randy was selected to the hall of fame on the first ballot. but, it's what he did that day that brings me joy. he wore a tie (swipe for picture no. 2) that featured the names of black people killed by police and told them that they will not be forgotten, that we stand with them, and that their families are not alone. on the biggest day of his career, he used his platform to shine a light. yeah...randy's the best! "straight cash, homie!" #bhm #blackexcellence
name: Travis Walker
tweet_full:
randy moss 
there is a distinction between "greatest" and "best". for example, jerry rice is the "greatest" wide receiver in nfl history. he has the records and the rings to back that up. but, if you are asking about the "best"? that's randy moss! in terms of playmaking ability that can change the game, moss can not be topped. he himself holds records and played in a couple of super bowls. but, that's not why randy is on here. yes, he's a mercurial talent. however, it is the drive and determination that got him to the league and what he's done afterward that impresses me. moss grew up in rand, west virginia, with a population of about 1,600. to say he was facing an uphill battle from the start would be an understatement. randy's college career began in fits and starts. he was going to play for notre dame, but after his involvement in a fight involving race (in west virginia?! shocked!) the fighting irish denied his enrollment. florida state was going to give him a chance, but he tested positive for marijuana after smoking a joint. yes, you read that right...one joint. so, they dismissed him. and just like that, the once promising career of randy moss was in jeopardy of never happening, having been shuttered before ever getting off the ground. that has happened to countless young black men. again...a joint! moss eventually ended up at marshall, a small school in a lesser division, but was still able to make it to the league. after his playing days were over, randy was selected to the hall of fame on the first ballot. but, it is what he did that day that brings me joy. he wore a tie (swipe for picture no. 2) that featured the names of black people killed by police and told them that they will not be forgotten, that we stand with them, and that their families are not alone. on the biggest day of his career, he used his platform to shine a light. yeah...randy's the best! "straight cash, homie!" #bhm #blackexcellence

text:
last weekend to see jane anger by @rosemarymezadesplas open til 8pm friday night. pictured here “absence if anger” hand sewn hair on fabric. artist’s own hair. 1. sojourner truth
2. bell hooks
3. wilma mankiller
4. installation view

jane anger features hand-sewn human hair drawings, watercolors and onsite installations. rosemary meza-desplas’ figurative artworks emphasize line and movement. the title refers to a 16th century pamphlet published in england titled jane anger, her protection for women.

meza-desplas explores the concept of anger as a tool for change by juxtaposing found imagery from social media, art history and mass media. she is interested in how the social movements, women’s marches and #metoo, harnessed anger in order to forefront an array of gender-based burdens. 
this exhibition includes meza-desplas’ most recent drawings which incorporate her gray hair. she has been sewing with her own hair since 2000. her hair is hand-sewn into a variety of grounds with small embroidery needles. meza-desplas’ decision to collect, sort and utilize hair as a vehicle for art-making is informed by socio-cultural symbolism, feminism and body issues, and religious symbolism. hair embodies a dichotomy: it can be sexy and engaging to people, on the other hand, it can be repulsive – like a hair in your soup or a hair on your hotel pillow. 
there are religious connotations to hair which coincide with symbolism reflecting strength, sensuality and reverence; such as delila cutting off samson’s hair and mary magdalen washing the feet of jesus with her hair.

“what purity culture did to me was wreck my sense of self-worth and i wasn’t even religious. 
purity culture perpetuates the rape culture that runs rampant in our society.

text:

och att kvinnor ska hitta styrkan att anmäla och offentliggöra dessa usla beteenden.
och att skammen bör ligga hos gärningsmännen.

tillsammans är vi starka!

tack, du hjälper andra! kram.

text: women deserve the increased success they are getting.  they’ve been oppressed for far too long.  they’re hungrier and more motivated than most men; and i applaud it.  success and achieving anything we want in life is a matter of patience.  if we can get through the rough, we can keep going when the system is expecting us to stop, we will achieve extraordinary results.  the proof is in our consistency to approach each day with grit.  repetition can be boring or tedious;  which is why so few people ever master it or complete anything.  as a black man i know minorities have limited opportunities to transform and we usually lose our consistency when we compare our beginning to someone else’s middle. 🤯#blakeiris #challengethewise #quotes #metoo #thursday #wordsofencouragement #inpirationalquotes #motivationalquotes #life #lifequotes #love #wordsofwisdom #wisdom #words

text:
this week, the topic tribal wounds has been weighing heavily on my heart. ❤️ what i see happening in the larger community and in the tantric community specifically is complex and nuanced. a tribal wound is surfacing. we see brutal competition amongst women. close-knit groups forming and acting with hostility. 
we see women angry from past wounds and transgressions, taking men down with impunity. 
and while i wanted to speak, i haven't yet because the landscape is so incredibly complicated.

#metoo was and still is so important.

giving voice to sexual trauma is so important.

but killing each other energetically to get a point across is never the answer.

while i don't know the answer, i do feel the healing of this is through union of opposites and the building of bridges. 
i believe that it's time to educate each other, listening and speaking openly and in equal balance. what is it like to be a woman in this world? what is it like to be a man in this world? can we find common ground for conversation? are we ready and willing to reconcile? 
using my platform, i would love to facilitate this.

in our class secrets of sexual ecstasy, we dig deep into the messages, myths, and programming we received growing up.

men are supposed to pursue, to score, to aggressive and chase relentlessly. if you’ve had a lot of sex as a man, you’re a stud, praised and celebrated amongst your peers.

in this social binary, women are expected to be chaste and virginal, legs closed, voices meek, always the prey never the pursuant. if you have a lot of sex as a woman, you're labeled a slut. 
do you see how these are diametrically opposed and how rape culture is perpetuated from the very beginning of our (desperately lacking) social education?

it’s time to come together and learn. learning how to say yes when we mean yes, and no when we mean no. learning the signals of our body. learning how to communicate our desires, needs, and wants. learning to listen to one another, hearing the yes’s and the no’s, then respecting them. these are a few ways we can start to undo our programming and update our "software" so to speak. but it requires everyone’s participation. #sensualalchemy

text:
“what is it like to live in a culture where it often seems like it is a question of when, not if, a woman will encounter some kind of sexual violence?” roxane gay
————————————————————————————
i have slowly come to terms with the fact that the ‘things’ that happened to me that i once believed to be insignificant, and something that happens to every girl at least once in her life, were traumatic, life changing experiences.
⠀⠀
my trauma history will look different from every person’s perspective. one person may think, “wow, i couldn’t imagine going through those things,” while another may scoff at my attempt to call what i’ve been through “trauma” since their history of abuse is miles longer than mine.
⠀⠀
the fact is: there will always be a case that seems worse than yours. but does that mean we should invalidate our own experiences because they can’t compare to surviving some other horrific event that is somehow deemed more valid than ours?
⠀⠀
over time i have learned to live with this truth. i am living a life i never thought imaginable just a few short years ago. 
your pain, your trauma and your feelings are valid and real. don’t let anyone diminish your story or your plight. 🌿

text:
day 4 of #fiveinfive
suffer the little children
“the trauma responses that followed my own experience with sexual abuse/assault created a vast gulf between me and god. one that i wasn’t even aware of until i was 40. church had become a great mask for me. a place to cover up my pain, instead of a safe space to heal. i was taught--inadvertently or not--by the church that this was ok. it was not.” - @tmlgwriter - writer, educator, and chief creative officer, @nsbbooksandmedia --
for far too many, sexual abuse and assault is a kind of rite of passage in our adolescence and young adulthood. so much so that we carry enough trauma to keep therapists (and liquor stores, if we’re honest) in business forever. sadly, the church and some of its leaders have a long history of protecting perpetrators, victim blaming, and/or simply being silent on these issues. this, opposed to being the ultimate defenders of girls and women who have experienced these violations. one also cannot ignore the fact that there are theologies that actually support these responses—theologies that survivor/writer tracey m. lewis-giggetts believes is the antithesis to the message of jesus. 
church girls [too] simultaneously challenges these theologies while offering women and girls of faith like tracey a voice to finally say, “enough!”
--
coming fall 2019

#metoo #churchtoo #metoomvmt

text:
we wrote this song ‘stories’ the week that #metoo broke out around the world, and shot the video at the hollywood #metoo march. 
the song is reflective of the feelings that emerged in us that week - that had been hidden deeply within the psyche of so many of us. it felt like this deep dark shame and pain had been buried deep down inside the earth and that week it rose to begin its bid for freedom...which was the strangest mix of absolute pain and also celebration of the liberation of such darkness.

just feeling reflective now - at this point in time looking back as to how the world has changed since then, and is still changing, as a result. we still have such a long way to go of course - but it feels positive. women are rising...minorities are being given a platform...it feels like voices from all walks of life are slowly being given an opportunity to step into visibility. and that really proves that the lyric in this song is true - ‘with our stories we break down the walls’. let’s keep sharing our stories and making this world a place of love, support and viability for all. ❤️✊🙏 (full video on youtube and igtv - ‘stories’ by unsung lilly)

text:
hi, my name is roxanne darling (@roxannedarling) and this is my week to takeover instagram from the los angeles center of photography (lacp) @la_centerofphoto. i am an emerging artist currently living in santa fe, nm. i love that lacp welcomes out-of-state photographers to be part of their community. this week, let's talk about bodies, nature, and getting older!

image: 
i am: resting in the redwoods

the photos i’m sharing this week are of me, from my series of portraits in nature. as a 66-year-old woman and emerging artist, i’m exploring the:
* the natural desire to be unclothed outdoors, in the privacy of precious places;
* a newly discovered quality of self-acceptance for my aging self;
* an appetite to create art from the female gaze, as a type of reclaiming my time, my body, and my point of view.

the photos were taken in 2017-2018 on an extended rv trip around the western us with my partner. in many cases, the place itself spoke up first and invited me to explore ways of finding myself in nature. as a card-carrying member of the #metoo movement, i hope this work conveys a type of freedom of self-expression that is possible regardless of one’s painful past experiences.

the photos were shot using several cameras: iphone, dji drone, and a canon dslr. all images have been cropped square; some images have been slightly modified to meet instagram rules. *
*
*
#lacpinstagramtakeover #lacp #losangelescenterofphotography #lacpmember #lacenterofphoto #womenphotographers #picoftheday #iam #santafeartist #freethinker

text: a statue depicting the famous image of a sailor kissing a woman in times square to celebrate the end of world war ii was spray-painted with graffiti that read "#metoo" in sarasota, florida (pictured here). while many consider the iconic kiss an act of spontaneous joy, in today's #metoo era, some activists view it as an act of sexual assault — given that the sailor admitted to not having the nurse's consent. the vandalism occurred one day after the death of george mendonsa, the sailor who inspired the statue. #history #statue #sculpture #kiss #florida #sarasota #metoo #brut #brutamerica

text_retweet:
it's been 5 years since i dropped a book with just my name on it.
it's time. 
this fall, i have a book releasing.
it's probably the hardest thing i've ever written. 
but it's also necessary. 
#storiesheal  repost from @nsbbooksandmedia - day 4 of #fiveinfive
suffer the little children
“the trauma responses that followed my own experience with sexual abuse/assault created a vast gulf between me and god. one that i wasn’t even aware of until i was 40. church had become a great mask for me. a place to cover up my pain, instead of a safe space to heal. i was taught--inadvertently or not--by the church that this was ok. it was not.” - @tmlgwriter - writer, educator, and chief creative officer, @nsbbooksandmedia --
for far too many, sexual abuse and assault is a kind of rite of passage in our adolescence and young adulthood. so much so that we carry enough trauma to keep therapists (and liquor stores, if we’re honest) in business forever. sadly, the church and some of its leaders have a long history of protecting perpetrators, victim blaming, and/or simply being silent on these issues. this, opposed to being the ultimate defenders of girls and women who have experienced these violations. one also cannot ignore the fact that there are theologies that actually support these responses—theologies that survivor/writer tracey m. lewis-giggetts believes is the antithesis to the message of jesus. 
church girls [too] simultaneously challenges these theologies while offering women and girls of faith like tracey a voice to finally say, “enough!”
--
coming fall 2019

#metoo #churchtoo #metoomvmt

text:
i had a rough relationship with my body growing up. i was bigger than the girls at my catholic elementary school and i was also the only asian girl. i envied their thin bodies and big eyes and wished for blonde hair.
⚡️
in 7th grade, i got lyme disease. the medicine i was on caused me to lose my appetite. i dropped weight quickly. when i went off the meds, i tried to maintain my unhealthily thin body. i developed body dysmorphia, constantly seeing myself as too big and in need of dropping more weight.
⚡️
from then til 9th grade, i became obsessed with counting calories and working out. i avoided sugar and drank only water. i was constantly cranky. at some point, i snapped out of it. i owe a lot of that to @blogilates and her ability to make working out fun and about becoming strong, not skinny. my mindset shifted because of her workout videos. i’m even wearing workout clothes from her line, @popflex_active in this shot.
⚡️
eventually, i stopped working out as much. i stopped restricting my calories and started eating what i wanted. i felt guilty about this, but eventually came to a place where i loved myself enough to stop feeling bad for prioritizing my life differently.
⚡️
then i had my first boyfriend. he, among many other men i let into my life, took advantage of my body and damaged the already tenuous relationship i had with it. it took years for me to call what happened to me sexual assault. even now, years later, my body holds onto that trauma, even as my mind knows that i’m safe now. cam has dealt with the brunt of it as i’ve continued to work through my trauma and i’m so blessed to have someone so patient by my side.
⚡️
when i was younger, i thought these struggles would break me, but i’m stronger now and i know in my core that i am powerful and i am in control of my own destiny and story. when i saw that @blogilates was having her first ever brand ambassadors for my favorite ever activewear company, i had to apply. #iamapowergirl.
⚡️
all right friends. if you made it this far, thank you! drop me a comment and let me know what makes you a power girl.
📸: @patrickspurlock / edit by me

from then til 9th grade, i became obsessed with counting calories and working out. i avoided sugar and drank only water. i was constantly cranky. at some point, i snapped out of it. i owe a lot of that to  and her ability to make working out fun and about becoming strong, not skinny. my mindset shifted because of her workout videos. i’m even wearing workout clothes from her line,  in this shot.
⚡️
eventually, i stopped working out as much. i stopped restricting my calories and staed eating what i wanted. i felt guilty about this, but eventually came to a place where i loved myself enough to stop feeling bad for prioritizing my life differently.
⚡️
then i had my first boyfriend. he, among many other men i let into my life, took advantage of my body and damaged the already tenuous relationship i had with it. it took years for me to call what happened to me sexual assault. even now, years later, my body holds onto that trauma, even as my mind knows that i’m safe now. cam has dealt with the brunt of it as i’ve continued to work through my trauma and i’m so blessed to have someone so patient by my side.
⚡️
when i was younger, i thought these struggles would break me, but i’m stronger now and i know in my core that i am powerful and i am in control of my own destiny and story. when i saw that  was having her first ever brand ambassadors for my favorite ever activewear company, i had to apply. amapowergirl.
⚡️
all right friends. if you made it this far, thank you! drop me a comment and let me know what makes you a power girl.
📸:  / edit by me

text:
ꮆꭵꮢꮮs ꮲꮃꮢ♀️❤️🙆
recently the discourse of women's rights grew up in society, movements like #metoo #bringbackourgirls
have attracted attention to violence against women happening everywhere today and now, in 21st century.🤦 although what is feminism actually and do we have to support this? ➡️❓ feminism -the advocacy of women's rights on the ground of the equality of the sexes. (according to oxford dictionary, though there are many more definitions that are deferentiating in a certain range).
historically there are 4 🌊🌊🌊 (actually same as democracy 🤔,but it is already too far): 1)  1830-1/2 1900
girls want: to vote, have equal property and contract rights. she wants to be participative in the society.backdays she was supposed to agree with the mind of her husband (and he really was a "trump" voter)
2) 1960s-80s
after ww2 period - sex, drugs & rock'n'roll. girls want to have sex and talk about this openly, to work, to make own decisions about personal life (if to merry a guy, than bcs of ❤️). and yes, she can not only cook you a pie!
3)1990s-2000s 
she is individual, she can do whatever?! btw there are some other people in community, not only 👨👩. we see a 🌈🌈🌈
4) 2000s - todayyyy
 please pay us equally💸, cause our gender doesn't influence the way we work
please don't hesitate and say about your feelings #metoo - no one judges you for being violated!
😎 micropolitical issues

so today we are allowed to go to the university, but if everywhere? today we can kiss our partners openly, but if everywhere? today we have many more challenges to fight over, but less than back in the beginning of this way. so let's value what we have now and struggle for even better equal future? 🤗
.
.
.
.
.

text:
do you ever feel like your head is exploding, imploding or your thoughts are wandering? this week i have mixed up a lot of timings, made rookie mistakes, feel a wee bit childish... i listened to the book “educated” by tara westover for my book club and it shook me to my core. i can’t even tell you, like all i could do between job hunting and interviews this week was to walk around cold london like a zombie, listening to tara’s voice pealing through the sky, slicing through the silence of thousands, millions of victims... giving herself a voice and speaking so eloquently about the pain and confusion experienced because of abuse and manipulation—in this she gives a voice to these many many many of us who cannot speak. yet. 
yet, yet, yet. 
#metoo #educated #tarawestover #idahobecrazy #books #abuse #believevictims

text:
hi guys! i’ve been working on a lot lately. one of those things being expressing my feelings regarding social awareness in more ways than one- although i’m no where near being a “poet” here’s an excerpt of “driving with fire.” a spoken word a wrote to spread awareness on domestic abuse, violence, and dating violence. please let me know what you think. enjoy. ✨
.
caution: a pretty long poem awaits.
.
we’re driving
the sun is shining
i look over at you,
you’re smiling so politely
your hair is whipping in the wind,
like a wild fire in the california mountains
you ignite something inside of me.
.
i don’t know why i feel this way.
.
it trembles within me.
you triggered it.
you’ve sparked it.
.
my mind quakes
tick.
my body shakes 
tick.
my heart aches
tick.
.
i don’t know why i feel this way.
.
i look at you and it’s like nothing else matters,
your presence is like sun rays.
but my mind is like an earthquake.
.
it shines down on me.
this feeling inside me,
it’s rumbling, growling.
sometimes it’s too hot, 
sometimes it isn’t enough.
sometimes it’s just right.
.
like the purple spots that appear in my sight,
after staring at the sun too long
you leave your mark on me.
you are your own sun.
you don’t need the light of day.
you make your mark on me.
.
i’m shaking.
tick.
.
i want you loudly
like gun powder and flame
it’s hard to resist you,
when i’m not used to the resistance.
everyone else grabs your attention so easily 
but with me you create the distance
.
the flame is low, will you reignite me?
it’s blue and cold,
like the night sky, i’m lost in the mystery of your soul.
you’re a constellation.
and i’m slowly aligning the stars.
this is a heavy transformation.
.
i used to remember a red, orange, yellow feeling.
i recognize it inside of me.
.
my mind quakes
tick.
my body shakes
tick.
my heart aches
tick.
.
am i flammable?
tick.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
#spokenword #domesticawareness #abuseawareness #instagram #metoo #fire #flame #domesticviolence #living #breath #justdoit #poetry #poems #love #family #division #photooftheday #newyork #vscocam #artist #photography #photographer #travelphotographer

text: phoebe robinson and jessica williams might be saying goodbye to 2 dope queens after its upcoming second season, but they're doing anything but disappearing. the duo, who vaulted their popular podcast to a series of hbo specials, are bringing the project to an end after its second season for a good reason: they're just too damn busy with their various books, tv writing gigs, and movie roles. (in fact, jessica's latest film, corporate animals, is making its debut at the sundance film festival.) we caught up with jessica and phoebe at an hbo brunch in their honor at sundance, where we also witnessed a panel discussion between the dopest of queens and cnn political commentator angela rye. the panel covered everything from hair braiding and beatboxing to michelle obama — a former guest on the podcast — whom jessica said "was very hydrated. her skin was like mmmmmmm. like when you bite into candied yams and you're like, 'these are amazing.'" speaking of women in politics, our interview happened on a notable day in the news, with sen. kamala harris officially kicking off her presidential campaign. during her conversation with jessica and phoebe, angela wondered about the sexism and racism we've already seen lobbed at harris. "it's been so interesting to me to see the number of sheer haters she had just out the gate, and a lot of it's not even based on real information," angela said. "how afraid are you all that folks aren't doing their research and finding out what's real and what's not? it doesn't mean that people don't deserve to be critiqued — all of us do. but people need to be critiqued on the facts." phoebe answered: "i think as much as liberals really mean well and they really want to hold people accountable, i think a lot of times there's a quickness to be like, 'if you're not perfect, you're canceled.'" that relevant insight was just one of many we heard sunday afternoon — read on for our conversation with phoebe and jessica about self-care, #metoo, and playing the flute with lizzo.  source: popsugar #blackwomen #talent #art #success #beauty #phoeberobinson #jessicawilliams

text: *read this all the way through or don’t*  when i heard the former sailor of the “#unconditionalsurrender” fame died i knew “#metoo” would be next. and i think that’s fine. we’re all allowed to look at images and feel whatever we want. i saw the photo growing up. for some time before i read on my own, i thought the image was of a couple and the kiss consensual. later i learned what actually happened (2nd pic for quote from former nurse). i saw the statue in the first pic by the #ussmidway in san diego when i went on vacation and stayed at the hotel with a view of both. this pic is not mine, we went at night and it was beautiful. i can’t explain why but the photo, the statue in person, the story behind it ... makes me happy. the vandalized “metoo” statue is in fl i believe. a soldier finds out he’s not going to war, a cheer and celebration in times square, an overly exuberant kiss... i feel like we’re getting to the point in society where we are willfully disengaging from the human experience. let me caveat what i’m about to say... i grew up around very ultra conservative muslim fundamentals. my family was not, but since we were muslim “enough,” orthodox muslims were in our circle. and it was absolutely suffocating. men who knew me would walk past me and say hello without looking in my direction. and it made me feel dirty. at 10 years old i was made to feel a man could be sexually provoked by looking at me. i’ve lived on the other side where rules reign supreme. when you never know who to shake hands with, who will embarrass you by refusing human touch, if a kiss can be just love and happiness and not wrought with icky sex, if you never get to discern intention and allow others to feel, how do you consider that living? why do we always have to lose the middle? not every move and every moment in time has to be vilified or suspect. does that resonate? #savethekiss

text: today i did something i’ve needed to do for a long time. for months i’ve let this boy play games and message me when he was bored and be extremely rude to me but i would let him and i didn’t block him from all my accounts because part of me said that if i just let him have a chance he’d get better. recently he messaged me again and i thought he was finally gonna try and be my friend again and i let him follow my accounts and responded and what not, but soon after he found something out he unfollowed my accounts. today he tried to message me after literally trying to cut himself out of my life. all my friends have been telling me to do this for a long time so surprise beach! hes blocked now! i bet y’all are proud. ngl kinda disappointed because i thought he changed but it’s whatever (psa this meme is directed at him and no one else)  #illuminati #meme #memes #funnymemes #memesfordays #relatablememes #same #relatable #me #metoo #tooreal #qualitymemes

text:
“i was scared of my husband, he often threatened to kill me,” said rakeyia, sharing memories from the five years of domestic abuse she suffered inside her two-room concrete house. “my husband would slap me and then beat my body when i asked for money for housekeeping or to take care of the children.” now her life is no longer dominated by fear. her village is one of 20 rural communities in ghana which have piloted department for international development community based action teams (combat). and so far, it appears to be working: women in participating villages have reported a 50 per cent reduction in physical partner violence over 18 months.

for more on this, visit the article by sarah newey at the telegraph: https://tinyurl.com/y44mzzvx

follow me @simontownsley for updates, outtakes, unpublished and archive material on this and future projects.

a graphic essay on the #metoo movement in india. 
this essay addresses sexual harassment at the workplace in india, and how many have reacted to it. 
it is a deeper look at the #metoo movement in india, for which i’ve collaborated with the polis project ( @thepolisproject ). if you think this message is important, relevant or have faced similar questions in discussions about the movement, please consider sharing this! 
the entire essay is available on the polis project’s website, and is linked in my bio. it’s best viewed on a larger screen, so pleaseee do me and your eyesight a favour and check it out on the website!

keeping victim’s identity secret, is not a conspiracy, but a responsibility. we can’t sell her name, to benefit few. we want to fight this, keeping a victim anonymous, her strength is the light, a sword to fight against evil,  what she has stood for and what we are battling, will make the coming generations alert, safe & secure.

recall- a delhi-gang rape, the whole country either academia, business, media, entertainment, determinately fought the without questioning who’s & what’s about victim. the way the case was dealt strengthened victim’s father to take her name in the end saying “ we want the world to know her real name. my daughter didn't do anything wrong, she died while protecting herself. i am proud of her” 
this is an example. set by our next door neighbor, where what happens to women, is not rare, but how they deal with it is lesson-full. this is why #metoo gained momentum there, and filthy ones have to give up their careers. instead of asking for victim’s identity, let’s create an environment where she feels her name to be taken ! #ibelieveher

text:
trigger warning ⚠️ - rape

dear monsters:
this ones for the monsters. the rapists. the molesters. the abusers. the sheep who are so pitifully weak and tiny that they feel empowered by beating a being half their size. the ways in which you treat and view woman have driven this existence into the ground. women are horrified. we purposely rent apartments on the highest floors of buildings. we run to our doors and lock them quickly but then stare at windows all night wondering if you will come through. we are scared to go on dates because we are aware that at any second you can change your mind about our worth and take whatever it is you want from us. we are scared to have daughters. we pray to have sons not because we would prefer one, but because the thought of watching your daughter cry herself to sleep like you do after being savagely raped is too much to bare. all because of you. all because along the way you decided that your sexual pleasure was more important than another being’s safety, sanity and innocence. 
dear men:
in your purest form you are strong, light, balanced, protective and gentle. i am grateful to you and the inner work you have done to become the ethereal beings that you are. men, we need your help. there are a lot of monsters out there but they just don’t listen to us. when we beg and cry, they only hurt harder. they are usually bigger and although we are strong beyond measure, sometimes we can’t fight them off. help us by talking about women like humans. the same way you speak of your mother who’s womb brought you into existence. help us by not making or laughing at jokes that continue to demean us. every time you’re compelled to call a woman a “whore” please pause and consider what that word implies. it may seem harmless for you but for us it’s life or death. help us create a new culture where woman are honoured as the loving, pure, wise beings that we are. help create a culture where our abusers are held accountable for their actions so that we don’t have to suffer in fear. so that more of us will report the injustices we have suffered. we were strong enough to survive, please be brave enough to help. thank you 💚

text:
there is no paved road for trauma survivors to recover. however, my experience has taught me that there is an internal road map written by my intuition, communicated through my body, paved by my energy, and illuminated by my creativity. all of me wants to heal, so i arise everyday and ask myself: how do i trust my intuition better today? how do i nourish my body? how do i listen to my energy? how do i surrender to my creativity? ~
what has your recovery journey been like? how are you being present to it? .
.
.
#recovery #metoo #trauma #help #healing #women #peace #happiness #fulfillment #hope #spirituality

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. he’s the only straight man i’ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- she [rebekah mercer] loved me. she was like, oh we need more of your type on our side!

your type? - the gays. she loved the gays. so did steve [bannon]. he saw us as early adopters. he figured, if you can get the gays on board, everyone else will follow. it’s why he was so into the whole milo [yiannopoulos] thing.

robert mercer was a pioneer in ai and machine translation. he helped invent algorithmic trading – which replaced hedge fund managers with computer programs – and he listened to wylie’s pitch. it was for a new kind of political message-targeting based on an influential and groundbreaking 2014 paper researched at cambridge’s psychometrics centre, called: - computer-based personality judgments are more accurate than those made by humans.
.
- in politics, the money man is usually the dumbest person in the room. whereas it’s the opposite way around with mercer, says wylie. - he said very little, but he really listened. he wanted to understand the science. and he wanted proof that it worked.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign’s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there “could have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating”. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday’s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnn’s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analytica’s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan’s app may not have been completely deleted. kogan’s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analytica’s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received repos that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan’s app may not have been completely deleted. kogan’s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided ceifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received repos that, contrary to the ceifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending fuher information.

special counsel robe mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal repoed in december. the firm complied to the request.

text:
#tbt to last year’s #reclaimthenight 🙌🏼 we’ll be marching again tonight, gathering at owens park from 6.30pm. 
_
since 2016 reported cases of sexual harassment has risen by 64%.
_
enough is enough.
_
we are calling on manchester city council to:
- improve the street lighting provisions in student areas. we also call for an increased police presence.
- stop the cuts to women’s shelters and increase funding for local services that support victims.
- do more to increase awareness of where victims can report acts of harassment, assault and violence. 
_
we also call on the council to encourage more organisations to become hate crime reporting centres. we hope to double the number of third party hate crime reporting centres in manchester by 2020.
_
it’s time for action. it’s time for the council to finally make women’s safety on the streets a priority.
_
it’s time to reclaim the night!

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytica $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text_retweet:
#quiltcon2019 is happening again right now. you may or may not get into quilting or other fiber arts, but to me... quilts are one of the original subversive arts. 
art born out of pure necessity, out of human need for shelter, as you piece your fabric in meditation, your emotions will come through. /bj

#repost @huntersds with @get_repost
・・・
“why i’m a feminist”
🧡. it’s a personal story. it’s the story of so many of the things that have happened to me that showed me where my rights aren’t equal. where the world has been constructed for the privilege of men. where my body is not considered my own. where i’ve been penalized for being a woman, a mom. where the expectations of being nice anyway have cornered me and silenced me. where i knew something felt wrong but no one taught me it wasn’t okay. 🧡. i’m really proud of #metoo, but a lot of ugly things can hide beneath the hashtag. you know there is pain under there, but unless the story is told, you can avoid seeing it’s horrors. so i told my story. 🧡
as yet, every single woman i have shown this to has said yes, she could tell a similar story. every woman. and many of them have been matter-of-fact about it. think about that. this is systemic at an incredibly huge level. it happens to all of us, all the time. death by a thousand cuts. 🧡.
while this work is my story, i think the real story is that so many of us can tell a similar one. it breaks my heart, yet fires me up to fight, to vote, to speak up. 🧡.
i’m an artist. art is one of my languages, so i speak up here. we have used embroidery for centuries to learn our letters but also to teach our stories. so i used my needle to write mine. 🧡. made in 2018. digitally designed and hand embroidered by me. quilted by my dear friend @nstovall of @justquilting. and honored with 3rd place in the handwork category at quiltcon 2019.

- she [rebekah mercer] loved me. she was like, oh we need more of your type on our side!

your type? - the gays. she loved the gays. so did steve [bannon]. he saw us as early adopters. he figured, if you can get the gays on board, everyone else will follow. it’s why he was so into the whole milo [yiannopoulos] thing.

robert mercer was a pioneer in ai and machine translation. he helped invent algorithmic trading – which replaced hedge fund managers with computer programs – and he listened to wylie’s pitch. it was for a new kind of political message-targeting based on an influential and groundbreaking 2014 paper researched at cambridge’s psychometrics centre, called: - computer-based personality judgments are more accurate than those made by humans.
.
- in politics, the money man is usually the dumbest person in the room. whereas it’s the opposite way around with mercer, says wylie. - he said very little, but he really listened. he wanted to understand the science. and he wanted proof that it worked.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
mark your calendar to attend "pushing back: from circe to #metoo" at the schweitzer brentwood library in the community room, march 26 at 7 p.m. it's sure to be an inspirational event when you hear how the stories of circe, captain marvel and the #metoo movement all revolve around women speaking up and fighting back.

missouri state university professors, dr. erin kenny, michael frizell and dr. holly holladay, will connect centuries-old powerful female deities, modern american-made superheroines and current movements in the media for a stirring discussion of female power and where we go from here.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
celery juice
.
all.the.rage. am i right? or am i right?
.
well, i hopped on the train last summer. i’ve been drinking celery juice daily (when it’s available and i’ve missed a few days) 9 months now. let me tell you what it’s done for me....
.
last summer was the pinnacle of my anxiety, ptsd, panic attacks and situational depression due to my sexual assault the prior year. (yes, healing and trauma take a long time to heal, are triggered when we least expect it and everyone heals differently.)
.
anyways, i was in a dark, lonely place. it was awful. i had already been going to therapy for months but i had just begun speaking out and people i thought were close friends not only turned their back but called me a liar. i was spiraling. i was also regularly visiting with my doctor and was taking ambien to sleep most nights and had a pill to help with anxiety/panic as needed after i was admitted to the er for a night because i thought i was dying during my most severe panic attack.
.
it was then i realized something had to change. i either needed to get on medication regularly or do something drastic to get my mental/physical state better. so instead of turning to alcohol to numb myself as i did for the 3 months after my assault, i turned to food. in a healthy way. i spent hours researching and studying. i came across the @medicalmedium and decided celery juice first thing in the am was going to be my new coffee. i needed to drop caffeine as it was a huge anxiety trigger for me and my adrenals needed healing as they had been stressed to the max since the night of the assault.
.
i started drinking 16oz of celery juice every morning and within a week my anxiety had decreased. i went vegan (i had been vegetarian/vegan off and on for a decade) but after watching @dominionmovement i couldn’t bear the thought of being the cause of another living beings trauma and then energetically consuming that fear, anxiety and stress.
.
within two weeks i was sleeping through the night 5/7 nights a week without ambien and hadn’t taken a single anxiety pill. and i can say since june 2018 i still haven’t taken a single pill. 
more in comments👇🏽

text:
'dus jij stapt vanavond gewoon in de auto bij iemand die je alleen van instagram kent en je komt ophalen in amsterdam?' in gedachten hadden mijn lieve medecursisten marjolein van @echtegerechten.nl afgelopen dinsdag al geclassificeerd als potentiële seriemoordenaar 😂
de opluchting was groot toen ik woensdag weer gewoon in de les verscheen.
.
.
en dat was nog voordat ze hoorden dat we meteen doorreden naar een wel erg afgelegen parkeerterrein en belandden in een soort van garagebox 🙈. ik verzin dit niet 😅. het is natuurlijk ook best raar dat het vandaag de dag de normaalste zaak van de wereld is om offline af te spreken met mensen die je alleen online kent. en alhoewel ik de laatste ben om te beweren dat je daar niet over na hoeft te denken heb ik geen moment getwijfeld dat het niet om marjolein zou gaan. zoals met de meeste online-meets-offline ontmoetingen met andere foodies was het ook deze keer weer erg gezellig. .
.
onze foodietour begon dus in die garagebox bij uncle lee met 2 bakken korean fried chicken en eindigde bij perzisch restaurant rozengeur met een tafel vol perzische gerechten 😋 en een foodbaby 🤪
.
.
heb jij weleens afgesproken met iemand die je via social media hebt leren kennen? en is de gedachtenflits door je hoofd gegaan dat het weleens iemand anders zou kunnen zijn? of zijn het alleen mijn collega's die hier meteen aan denken 😉 .
.
ik ben inmiddels weer onderweg richting het (hopelijk) zonnige zuiden a.k.a. tilburg. .
.
#foodiesarethebest #foodiesmeetup #instameetup #perzischekeuken #koreanfriedchicken #koreaansekip #amsterdam #unclesam #rozengeur

i forgot to share this picture! i’m loving our living out the box journal. it’s portable, convenient and is a easy way to stay present in your self love journey! each day, you write what your grateful for, a to do list, your mood and answer 2 prompted questions. this should only take you 5-10minutes to complete! although it doesn’t take long, the benefits are lasting! journaling is a way of self expression and for most it’s easier to write your feelings than have to communicate them verbally! •

🌈
خیلی از ماها وقتی با پرسشی روبه‌رو می‌شویم شروع می‌کنیم به ترسیدن. وقتی گرایش جنسی‌مان را پذیرفتیم، ممکن است دلایل خودمان را داشته باشم و این مسئله را مخفی و محرمانه نگهداریم. این دوره مخفی‌بودن و رازداری، "در گنجه بودن" نامیده می‌شود.
.
هیچ مشکلی نیست که انسان گرایش جنسی‌اش را مخفی نگهدارد. ما همگی به زمان نیاز داریم تا به افکار و دل‌مشغولی‌های‌مان عادت کنیم. فقط به یاد داشته باشید که اگر از نظر عاطفی دچار مشکل می‌شوید و به‌ شما سخت می‌گذرد، تنها نمانید. کسی را که به او اعتماد دارید انتخاب کنید و فکر کنید اگر نگرانی خود را با او در میان بگذارید چه می‌شود. .
اگر با دوست‌تان دارید مطرح می‌کنید حواس‌تان باشد که از نظر و نگرش واقعی وی به همجنسگرایی مطلع شوید. بهتر است که قبلاً واکنش‌ دوست‌تان را تصور کنید. مثلاً بگویید که یکی از اعضای خانواده شما همجنسگراست، یا مثلاً بگویید مطلبی درباره حقوق همجنسگرایان در فلان وب‌سایت خوانده‌اید. بعد ببینید واکنش وی به این مسئله چه خواهد بود.
.
بعضی از همجنسگرایان در گنجه احساس امنیت بیشتری می‌کنند. همه مدارس و محیط‌های کاری امن نیستند. اگر ترجیح داده‌اید که "در گنجه" بمانید، به خودتان بگویید این موقتی است؛ وسیله‌ای برای زنده‌ماندن است.
.
درست است که در گنجه بودن امن است، اما بهداشتی و سالم نیست. وقتی مخفی هستید خیلی از حقوق زندگی آزاد را از دست می‌دهید و متحمل استرس می‌شوید و اعتماد به نفس‌تان را از دست می‌دهید. اگر در حال حاضر باید در گنجه بمانید، به این فکر کنید که چه زمانی برای "آشکارسازی" مناسب و امن است.
.
پ.ن: اشک‌های مادرش فقط به خاطر پنهان‌کاری ۱۶ ساله و ترس فرزندش از خودش بودن هست.
#آشکار_سازی 🏳‍🌈
#lgbt #comeout #metoo

text:
"virginia’s state seal depicts the deity virtus, breast bared with a spear and a sword in hand, standing over a man — tyranny — who is splayed on the ground with his crown fallen nearby. so for the two activists advocating for the ratification of the federal equal rights amendment — which aims to ensure equal rights for women — it seemed like a natural scene to emulate during a protest near the state capitol in richmond.

natalie white, an artist and vice president of the advocacy group equal means equal, played tyranny. michelle renay sutherland, 45, was virtus — the genius of the commonwealth, the state explains, and the personification of virtue. her left breast was exposed as part of the costume." --- for the entire article:

text:
icona di stile, personaggio eclettico, dandy d’altri tempi e camaleontico innovatore. tutti questi appellativi si prestano facilmente all’epica personalità che è stata karl lagerfeld. lo stilista si è spento la mattina del 19 febbraio 2019, all'età di 85 anni, nell’ospedale americano di parigi, a causa di un cancro al pancreas che da tempo lo aveva colpito. kaiser karl, come da molti era chiamato per via dell’imponenza della sua  cifra stilistica, nacque ad amburgo nel 1933 in una ricca famiglia tedesca. gli agi familiari gli permisero già nei primi anni 50 di approcciarsi al mondo della moda trasferendosi a parigi. nella capitale europea dello stile fu sempre circondato da personalità altrettanto camaleontiche e stuatuarie come yves saint laurent e pierre balmain, i quali in qualche modo influenzarono il suo modo di percepire la moda. nel 1954, con un bozzetto di un cappotto, vinse il woolmark prize. solo qualche anno più tardi però la sua vena artistica raggiunse la maturità. lagerfeld trovò nelle donne dissolute, bohèmienne ed eteree l’innovativo archetipo di bellezza di quegli anni. il profondo contrasto tra l’assoluto rigore dell’uomo tedesco e la sua concezione avanguardista di bellezza, diede vita ad alcune delle creazioni stilistiche più geniali del secolo. nel 1965 firmò un contratto a vita con fendi e nel 1974 fondò il proprio brand “lagerfeld”. dieci anni dopo prese le redini di chanel, riuscendo in pochi anni a far tornare il marchio al livello di status symbol, svecchiandolo da tendenze ormai obsolete e rendendolo pop, contemporaneo e innovativo. nel corso degli anni la sua personalità fu più volte criticata a causa di dichiarazioni molto controverse su temi di attualità quali l’uso delle pellicce nella moda, il movimento #metoo e l’eccessivo dimagrimento a cui le modelle dovevano sottoporsi. in ogni caso le critiche all’uomo non macchiano l’immagine di uno degli artisti più geniali e pionieristici del novecento. -phil

#karllagerfeld #moda #stile #fendi #chanel #accaddeoggi #yvessaintlaurent #sfilata #milano #parigi #modella #modelleitaliane #bellezza #beautiful #fotografie #fotografia #fotografo #stilista

text: but she didnt feel violated, or assaulted. she understood how important the end of a world war was. she understood his elation. she just happened to be similarly dressed as the nurses were that saved his friends lives. he was drunk on a date with someone else, saw her in her outfit, and was overcome with joy. assuming she was feeling the same joy, and relief. he kissed her.  in any other way, this would be assault (in this way ive been assaulted by women...no joke)  but given the circumstance, and that she didnt feel assaulted. and that years later, when they were discovered as those people. they met and became friends. and even sent christmas cards to each other. so no...it isnt a #metoo. you cant apply your emotions to anyone else. your opinion is not their reality. she came to america to escape war. now to see the horrors end.  and he saw his friends killed and die. if you cant see how those feelings can accumilate into an overwhelming action such as this, you have live an empty life.  morality doesnt exist in the face of inhumanity.

text:
para marcar seus 98 anos, completados na terça-feira (19), a #folha realiza ao longo desta semana uma série de eventos na sede do jornal, no centro de são paulo. 
nesta quinta-feira (21) as colunistas ilona szabó e katia rubio debatem o tema 'ser mulher em tempos de #metoo', com mediação de marcos augusto gonçalves. 
a programação é gravada e disponibilizada posteriormente no site da folha. a cobertura do evento de hoje você já pode acompanhar pelos nossos stories. 
nas imagens, algumas mulheres que participaram do movimento #metoo: lady gaga (anne-christine poujolat/afp), salma hayek (regis duvignau/reuters) e lupita nyong'o (image group la) #folha #folhadespaulo #fsp

text:
have you used whatsapp? are your kids using it? here's what you need to know....
whatsapp is a facebook owned social media app that allows users to make phone calls, text, and share photos and videos using a simple internet connection. because the platform uses an internet connection, your child can talk to anyone in their contacts anywhere in the world using a simple wifi connection. users in the european union must be at least 16 years old to use the app, while us users are only required to be 13 years old. whatsapp is a popular app because of its end to end encryption for calls and messaging. this makes it very attractive to local and international criminals. there is also a geo locator in the app so other users can see your location. as a parent, you should be concerned about a few things:
1. your child can talk to anyone around the world without the number ever showing up on your phone bill.
2. your child can receive and send inappropriate content that you won't ever see unless you open the app.
3. location services allow others to see your child's location.
4. the app has a group chat option so your child can be part of discussion with and/or receive content from adults with whom they should not be communicating with.
5. kids can be lured away from home and into criminal activity, such as sex trafficking, because of the apps encryption.
parents, we have to be more proactive about monitoring our kid's phones because these apps are the gateway for predators to gain access to your kids without ringing your doorbell or approaching them in public. these predators can spend days, weeks, months grooming your child right under your nose while your child is safely nested in your home. and, once they lure them out, the app's encryption may prevent you from discovering the predator's identity. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #superbowl

text:
when bae is sad they aren't all the way in the photo... seriously though look at the giant leaning statue of gold behind me. i've come a long way from being a kid on the streets of indy banging, breaking into houses, selling drugs, and hurting people. i've come a long way from a lot of things. it's not by luck and damn sure isn't by sitting around and not making decisions to change my life. i'm so grateful to be where i am in my life right now and this is just the beginning. i'm working on a few different ways to share my experiences in real palatable ways that other trauma warriors can utilize! it's coming soon.

just know this... you have the capacity to do anything! you just have to be willing do do the hardest thing: change.

text:
ayanna soyini pressely born february 3, 1974 was the first woman of color to be elected to boston city council in 2009. during her term as city council she created a committee of healthy women, families and communities to spotlight stable families reduce violence and poverty and promote women's issues.

a sexual assault survivor from childhood ms. pressely used her experience to spark and lead a public discussion in 2011 about the sexual assault epidemic years prior to the #metoo movement.

in 2016, ms. pressely was named one of "14 young democrats to watch" in the new york times.

in november 2018 the honorable ayanna pressley was the first black woman elected to congress. the united states house of representatives from massachusetts 7th congressional district.

#blackrepresentationmatters #blackdollsmatter #firstblack #makinghistory #americanherstory #historymaker #dolls #blackdolls

text:
for some reason theres a lot of shame and embarrassment that goes along with being the victim. people will talk as if it was plain as day that "you should have known". but, they don't show up as the villain, they come into your life as the hero and slowly become the villain. by then, you believe the hero to be true. by then, you love the hero and think they only want what's best for you. there is more than physical abuse involved, there is manipulation, control, emotional, and financial. instead of shaming the victim for not seeing something that you think is so clear, why not blame the monster behind it. .
.
.

text:
🚨 real talk post 🚨
the art of distraction
when you’re in pain 100% of your life, and it hurts just when someone hugs you, but you smile through it because you are so loved... or you don’t feel like facing the recovery process that 37yrs of narcissistic abuse put you in, because it’s not fun having to dissect the childhood you thought you knew... there’s an incredible thing that happens when you’re responsible for a 3mo ball of fur that looks to you for attention, love, and care. 😤🤯🥰
—
i woke up in the middle of the night with a brilliant idea. 💡 i thought: what if we got all the rescue dogs esa certified and matched them up with narcissistic abuse sufferers (or anybody that’s faced trauma, really)?? that would be saving 2 lives with 1 effort. 🤔🤷🏻‍♀️🐶
—

text_retweet:
#repost @jaringanmuda (@get_repost)
・・・
setiap orang berhak mendapatkan rasa
aman atas bentuk tubuh dan ekspresi gender, begitu pula dengan cara berpakaian dan ekspresi tubuh yang
lain. oleh karenanya pelabelan negatif seperti gambar diatas merupakan bentuk pelecehan seksual.

tidak ada "perempuan nakal, binal, bispak, sundal"!! dalam lingkungan masyarakat yang masih patriarkis, kita sering mendengar pelabelan negatif (stereotype) tersebut. perempuan yang mendapat stereotip seperti ini lebih rentan terhadap tindak pelecehan, karena masyarakat sendiri bahkan membenarkan tindak pelecehan terhadap perempuan yang mereka labeli demikian.

stereotype tersebut salah dan tidak dapat dijadikan landasan bagi siapapun untuk membenarkan tindak pelecehan seksual terhadap orang lain. label "perempuan baik-baik" ataupun "nakal, binal, bispak, sundal" adalah cerminan konstruksi sosial yang tidak setara, merupakan bentuk penghakiman moral dan kontrol terhadap tubuh perempuan.
